  "prompt": "If you want to go to graduate school in biophysics, should you major in physics or biology?",
  "response": "If you want to go to graduate school in biophysics, it's recommended to:\n\n1. Major in physics with a strong background in biology\n- Physics provides the mathematical and analytical skills essential for biophysics\n- Take additional biology courses to build biological knowledge\n\n2. Alternatively, major in biology with a strong mathematical and physics background\n- Take advanced physics and math courses\n- Consider minoring in physics or taking additional physics electives\n\n3. Ideal preparation would include:\n- Advanced coursework in both physics and biology\n- Calculus, differential equations, statistical mechanics\n- Molecular biology, biochemistry, genetics\n- Research experience in a biophysics-related lab\n\n4. Most important factors:\n- Strong quantitative skills\n- Research experience\n- Understanding of both physics and biological systems\n- Good GRE scores\n- Recommendation letters from research mentors\n\n5. Many graduate programs look for interdisciplinary preparation, so a well-rounded background in both physics and biology is most advantageous.\n\nThe best path depends on your specific strengths, interests, and the requirements of the graduate programs you're targeting.",
